area of syntactic change and the insight it provides on the nature of language. This volume represents the first major contribution on the mechanisms of syntactic change. The fourteen articles that make up this volume were selected from the Symposium on the Mechanisms of Syntactic Change held at the University of California, Santa Barbara, in 1976, one of a series of three conferences sponsored by the National Science Foundation. These papers clearly demonstrate that the generative approach to the study of language does not explain diachronic processes in syntax. This collection is enlightening, provocative, and carefully documented with data drawn from a great variety of language families.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / General.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChafe, Wallace, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChung, Sandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDixon, R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGivón, Talmy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaas, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHankamer, Jorge, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLangacker, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLangdon, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLi, Charles N., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLi, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMunro, Pamela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSteele, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat